                  </persName>
               
            .</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18210912-181-person1832">
                  WILLIAM 
                  HITCHCOCK
               <interp inst="t18210912-181-person1832" type="surname" value="HITCHCOCK"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18210912-181-person1832" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18210912-181-person1832" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a <rs id="t18210912-181-viclabel1061" type="occupation">publican</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18210912-181-victim1831 t18210912-181-viclabel1061"></join>, and live in <placeName id="t18210912-181-crimeloc1062">Old-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18210912-181-crimeloc1062" type="placeName" value="Old-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18210912-181-crimeloc1062" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18210912-181-off1059 t18210912-181-crimeloc1062"></join>. On the 14th of August, about half-past six o'clock at night, two gentlemen came into my parlour to write, and had a candlestick on the table. I went out, and did not miss it till the next morning; the prisoner was frequently at my house, selling buttons.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18210912-181-person1833">
                  SAMUEL 
                  BRADY
               <interp inst="t18210912-181-person1833" type="surname" value="BRADY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18210912-181-person1833" type="given" value="SAMUEL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18210912-181-person1833" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a publican, and live near Hitchcock. The prisoner came into my house on this night, about half-past ten o'clock, she said something, and two Scotch gentlemen said, "Turn that woman out;" I went to turn her out, and saw the candlestick sticking out of her pocket, I took it from her, she said it was her own; I sent for the watchman, who took her.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18210912-181-person1834">
                  JOHN 
                  TWEEDY
               <interp inst="t18210912-181-person1834" type="surname" value="TWEEDY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18210912-181-person1834" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18210912-181-person1834" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a constable. On the 14th of August, I took charge of the prisoner, and asked her what had become of the candlestick, she said she never saw it before.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18210912-181-person1835">
                  JOSEPH 
                  PRINCE
               <interp inst="t18210912-181-person1835" type="surname" value="PRINCE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18210912-181-person1835" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18210912-181-person1835" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I was taking the prisoner to the watch-house, she said if I would forgive her, she would shew me where she took it from - I took her to several houses, and when we came to the Rum Puncheon public-house, where Hitchcock lives, she said "That is it."</p>
               <p>(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>(The prisoner put in a written defence, stating, that she had drank rather freely, and did not know she had the candlestick. till it was found on her.)</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18210912-181-verdict1063" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18210912-181-verdict1063" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 63.</p>
               <p>
